cs.SI, cs.CR, cs.SOC, cs.IR, cs.HC 

This paper deals with the social influence of malicious URLs on social media, which falls under the category of social media analysis. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the security implications of these attacks, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). Additionally, the paper uses machine learning techniques to predict user behavior, which could place it under cs.IR (Information Retrieval) or cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Finally, the paper discusses social science concepts such as conformity and the bandwagon effect, which could place it under cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences).
